{{Wiktionarypar|schizophonia}} '''Schizophonia''' is a term coined by [[R. Murray Schafer]] to describe the splitting of an original sound and its electroacoustic reproduction.<ref>{{cite book | last = Schafer | first = R. Murray | title = The New Soundscape: a handbook for the modern music teacher | publisher = BMI Canada | year = 1969 | isbn = 0-900938-29-3 }}</ref> This concept comes from the invention of electroacoustic equipment for the transmission of sound, which meant that any sound could be recorded and sent anywhere around the world. Originally, that was not possible, as every sound was an original and could only be heard once. Schizophonia is the separation of this native sound and the recording of it.<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Music of the Environment|last = Schafer|first = Murray|publisher = |year = |isbn = 0826416144|location = |pages = }}</ref>
==In popular culture== * [[Mike Batt]] released an album in 1977 entitled ''Schizophonia'' * [[Rinôçérôse]] released an album in 2005 entitled ''[[Schizophonia (Rinôçérôse album)|Schizophonia]]'' * A number of albums are entitled the related term ''[[Schizophonic (disambiguation)|Schizophonic]]''
==See also== * [[Acousmatic sound]] * [[Acoustic ecology]] * [[Schismogenesis]] * [[Sound culture]] * [[Soundscape]]
